<article>

  <p>
    Mindfulness, as it circulates now, often means something thin: notice the present,
    return when you wander, leave the rest alone. That habit can help. It is not what
    the <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">Satipaṭṭhāna</span>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sutta" data-en="discourse">Sutta</span> is teaching.
  </p>

  <p>
    MN 10 — and its longer sibling, DN 22 — open with a hard claim. This is
    <em>ekāyano ayaṃ maggo</em>: the one-way path, the direct path. Not a side practice.
    Not a warm-up for the real teaching. The four foundations are given for the
    purification of beings, for the ending of sorrow and grief, for the attainment of
    the true way, for the realisation of
    <a href="/concepts/nibbana/"><span class="pali" data-pali="nibbāna" data-en="liberation">nibbāna</span></a>.
    The discourse is practical because it is aimed. Soft noticing without that aim is
    a different project wearing the same English word.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What a Foundation Is</h2>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">Satipaṭṭhāna</span>
    names both the discourse and the practice: establishing
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span> — clear,
    continuous knowing — in a domain of experience. A foundation is not a pedestal for
    a self to sit on. It is a place where attention can stand without collapsing into
    the story the mind prefers.
  </p>

  <p>
    The sutta does not ask the practitioner to invent a special inner life. It asks for
    accurate knowing of what is already occurring: body as body, feeling-tone as
    feeling-tone, mind as mind, phenomena as phenomena. The knowing is not cold
    detachment for its own sake. It is the condition under which clinging can be seen
    operating — and, with enough clarity, released.
  </p>

  <p>
    The four domains are not four unrelated meditations. They are successive apertures
    on the same stream of experience. Breath practice as mapped in the
    <a href="/suttas/anapanasati/">Āṇāpānasati Sutta</a> can move through all four
    without changing objects.
    <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">Satipaṭṭhāna</span>
    names the map. Breath is one way of walking it.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Four Domains</h2>

  <p>
    The discourse works each foundation the same way: name the field, offer specific
    contemplations, then return to a refrain that never changes. The inventory matters
    less than the orientation. Still, the four fields do different jobs.
  </p>

  <h3>Kāya — the body</h3>

  <p>
    Contemplation of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="kāya" data-en="body">kāya</span> begins where
    experience is hardest to fake: the living body. A
    <span class="pali" data-pali="bhikkhu" data-en="one on the path">bhikkhu</span> sits and knows
    a long breath as long, a short breath as short — clear knowing, not breath control.
    From there the field widens: postures; clear comprehension in ordinary activity;
    the body's parts; the four elements; the cemetery contemplations on decomposition.
  </p>

  <p>
    The sequence is not morbid theatre. It systematically dismantles the body's
    apparent solidity and permanence with the same clarity used on the breath. Body
    first, not because the body is sacred, but because identification with form is
    thick — and because what can be known here is always available.
  </p>

  <h3>Vedanā — feeling-tone</h3>

  <p>
    The second foundation is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>: the bare
    hedonic tone — pleasant, unpleasant, or neutral — that colors every moment.
    Worldly and spiritual feeling are distinguished; the instruction remains the same.
    Know pleasant as pleasant. Know unpleasant as unpleasant. Know neutral as neutral.
  </p>

  <p>
    Why this matters becomes clear in
    <a href="/concepts/paticca-samuppada/"><span class="pali" data-pali="paṭicca-samuppāda" data-en="dependent origination">dependent origination</span></a>.
    From feeling, craving tends to arise. Establishing
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span> on
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span> means catching
    the tone before the reactive machinery of wanting and not-wanting fully engages.
    That is not suppression. It is seeing in the gap between contact and the story that
    usually follows.
  </p>

  <h3>Citta — the mind's weather</h3>

  <p>
    The third foundation turns to
    <span class="pali" data-pali="citta" data-en="mind">citta</span> — mind as the
    quality of awareness in this moment. A mind with lust is known as with lust; without
    lust, as without. Hatred and its absence; delusion and clarity; contraction and
    scatter; developed and undeveloped; unified and not; liberated and not. The list is
    empirical. These are tones that can be observed now.
  </p>

  <p>
    The instruction is not, first, to renovate the weather. It is to know it accurately.
    A mind clouded by anger that knows itself as clouded has already opened a slight
    gap between the state and identification with the state. Unreflective mind does not
    have that gap. The knowing is not neutral. It is the beginning of being less owned
    by what is seen.
  </p>

  <h3>Dhammā — phenomena</h3>

  <p>
    The fourth foundation is the most expansive:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="phenomena">dhammā</span> as phenomena —
    mental objects and teaching categories encountered as live events. Here the
    practitioner contemplates the five
    <a href="/concepts/five-hindrances/"><span class="pali" data-pali="nīvaraṇa" data-en="hindrances">nīvaraṇas</span></a>
    — knowing each when present, when absent, and the conditions for arising, abandoning,
    and non-reappearance. Then the five
    <a href="/concepts/khandhas/"><span class="pali" data-pali="khandha" data-en="aggregates">khandhas</span></a>
    of clinging; the six sense bases and the fetters that arise dependent on them; the
    seven factors of awakening
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="bojjhaṅgā" data-en="factors of awakening">bojjhaṅgā</span>);
    and finally the four noble truths themselves.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is where doctrine stops being something one believes about experience and
    becomes something one can watch operating. The hindrances are not a theory of
    distraction. They are the distraction, known as such.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>The Refrain Is the Method</h2>

  <p>
    After each contemplation, the sutta repeats the same refrain — dozens of times,
    unchanged. The repetition is the point. It names the quality of attention that all
    the specific exercises share:
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "In this way, in regard to the body he abides contemplating the body internally,
    or he abides contemplating the body externally, or he abides contemplating the
    body both internally and externally. He abides contemplating the nature of arising
    in the body, or he abides contemplating the nature of passing away in the body,
    or he abides contemplating the nature of both arising and passing away in the body.
    Mindfulness that 'there is a body' is established in him to the extent necessary
    for bare knowledge and continuous mindfulness. And he abides independent, not
    clinging to anything in the world."
    <cite>— MN 10 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    Three moves run through it. First, internal and external:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span> is not only private
    introspection. One attends to this body, then to body as such, then to both — so
    practice does not collapse into self-absorption. Second, arising and passing:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">anicca</span> is not a
    conclusion saved for the end of the sit. It is what attention is trained to see
    throughout. Third, the closing orientation: not clinging to anything in the world.
  </p>

  <p>
    That last line is easy to skip past. It is the direction of the whole map. The
    contemplations are not techniques for becoming more comfortable inside experience.
    They are a systematic loosening of the grip.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Where Contemporary Mindfulness Parts Company</h2>

  <p>
    No other Pali text has shaped modern meditation culture quite like this one — and
    that influence has often flattened it.     In many presentations,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">Satipaṭṭhāna</span>
    becomes a chart of bare attention: present-moment awareness as a neutral skill, as useful
    for stress reduction as for liberation. The sutta itself is not neutral.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is anchored, throughout, in
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">anicca</span>,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="unsatisfactoriness">dukkha</span>, and
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anattā" data-en="non-self">anattā</span> — the
    <a href="/concepts/ti-lakkhana/">three characteristics</a>. Seeing body as body,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span> as vedanā,
    mind as mind, is not equanimity as a lifestyle goal. It is the recognition that none
    of what is seen is stable, finally satisfying, or a permanent owner of experience.
    The refrain says the aim out loud: not clinging to anything in the world.
  </p>

  <p>
    The discourse closes with a strong promise. One who practices in this way for seven
    years — or seven months, or seven days — should expect either full awakening or,
    if a remainder of clinging remains, non-return. Worth holding as the texts state it,
    without turning the numbers into a progress chart. The claim still matters: the path
    this sutta maps is not endless busywork. There is, the Buddha says, a shore on the
    other side.
  </p>

</article>
